Assessing Summary

  • Drop observations with missing Data
  • Convert type :
    • member_birth_year : to integer
    • bike_id : to string
    • start_station_id : to string
    • end_station_id : to string
    • start_time : to datetime
    • end_time : to datetime
  • Create new columns :
    • start_year, start_month, start_day, start_day_week, start_hour
    • end_year, end_month, end_day, end_day_week, end_hour
    • member_age & age_groups

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The original dataset contains 183412 observations (rides) and 16 features (duration_sec', 'start_time', 'end_time', 'start_station_id'...). After cleaning Data, we have deleted 8460 observations (missing Data) and added 7 features extracted from the original features (start_year', 'start_month', 'start_day', 'start_day_week', 'start_hour', 'member_age', 'age_groups').

  • The final dataset contains 174952 rides and 23 features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out :

  • Distribution of number of rides : what features have effect on number of rides
  • What features are best for predicting the duration of ride in the dataset

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think features like user_type', 'member_gender , member age, start_hour, start_day can be helpful for our investigation.

Univariate Exploration¶

Distribution of number of rides¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the number of rides by :

  • Gender
  • User type
  • age
  • Start day & hour

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • There were more male riders than female, and most members were subscribers compared to casual riders. The majority of the members young adults ( 25 to 34 years old).
  • The number of trips peaked around 7-10am and 16-19pm during a day (rush hours), there were more trips on work days (Mon-Fri) compared to weekends : Primary usage is probably for going to work.
  • Most rides were quick and short, lasted between 5 to 10 minutes, though there were some very long outliers like 24hrs
  • the log-scale distribution shows that rides were normaly distributed with a peak aroud 500s

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • The distribution of the trip duration was long-tailed at first plotting. I filtered out the outlier long trip records for the study, which made the distribution much clearer.
  • In order to help focusing on the main cases of typical use of the system, I added a log-scale plot of ride duration , which has a normal distribution.

# plot the categorical variables against duration
fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols = 3, nrows = 3 , figsize = [20,10])

for i in range(len(categoric_vars)):
    var = categoric_vars[i]
    
    # barplot
    # define x and y for barplot
    x = df1.groupby(var).duration_sec.mean().index
    y = df1.groupby(var).duration_sec.mean()
    # plot x and y using seaborn.barplot
    sb.barplot(x, y, color=base_color, ax = ax[0,i])
    # add x label and format it
    ax[0,i].set_xlabel(f'{var}', fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add y label and format it, add unit if exist
    ax[0,i].set_ylabel('Duration Average(s)' , fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add title and format it
    ax[0,i].set_title(f'Duration Average by {var}'.title(), fontsize=14, weight='bold')
    
    # violinplot
    sb.violinplot(data = df1, x = var, y = 'duration_sec', ax = ax[1,i],
               color = base_color)
    # boxplot
    sb.boxplot(data = df1, x = var, y = 'duration_sec', ax = ax[2,i],
               color = base_color)


plt.show()

Locking at the charts above, we find that :

  • The trip duration distribution is much narrower for subscribers compared to casual riders on the shorter/quicker trip end overall. It seems like subscribers have a more specific usage or targeted goal riding the bikes compared to customers who vary more and generally rented the bikes for longer.
  • Though not a huge difference, male riders tend to have shorter trips compared to female users, indicated by both a smaller median and shorter IQR
  • Age Groups have almost the same trip duration distribution.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There are a lot more subscriber usage than customers, more male than female. The riding habit/pattern varies a lot between subscribers and customers : Subscribers use the bike sharing system for work, whereas customers tend to ride for fun for longer. shorter trips were on work days (Mon-Fri) and especially during rush hours (when going to work in the morning and getting off work in the afternoon).

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶
